# An Examination of the Domestic Cat as a Cohabitant Species

The following slides constitute a thorough investigation of *Felis catus* in the context of human cohabitation, drawing on archaeological, behavioral, and cultural evidence accumulated over approximately eleven thousand years of mutual adaptation.

---

# On the Question of Awesomeness

The proposition that cats are awesome is, on its face, a value judgment that resists empirical verification, but a careful enumeration of their characteristics — low-maintenance feeding patterns, near-silent ambient presence, demonstrated efficacy in rodent population control, body temperatures that render them functionally equivalent to portable heating elements during cold months, and a baseline self-sufficiency that distinguishes them from virtually every other domesticated animal — provides what we will argue constitutes a strong inferential case in the affirmative.

---

# Anatomical Considerations

A domestic cat possesses, on average, fifty-three vertebrae compared to the thirty-three found in the human spine, a difference that accounts for the well-known flexibility of the species; furthermore, the feline ear contains approximately thirty-two distinct muscles per side, allowing for independent rotation of each ear in pursuit of acoustic stimuli; the whiskers serve a proprioceptive function, providing the animal with continuous data about the dimensions of nearby openings; and the larynx, despite its relatively small size, generates the characteristic purring sound at frequencies between twenty-five and one hundred fifty hertz.

---

# The Phenomenon of Purring

Purring is a behavior unique among the felidae in that it can occur during both inhalation and exhalation, producing a continuous low-frequency vibration that serves multiple ethological functions including but not limited to maternal bonding with kittens, self-soothing during periods of stress or injury, communication of contentment to human caregivers, and — most intriguingly — the apparent stimulation of bone density and tissue regeneration through frequencies that fall within ranges used in certain forms of physical therapy, leading some researchers to characterize the purring cat as a self-administering medical apparatus.

---

# Predatory Capabilities

Among large terrestrial predators the lion exhibits a hunting success rate of approximately twenty-five percent, the wolf approximately fourteen percent, and the polar bear approximately ten percent, while the domestic house cat — despite its diminutive size — achieves a success rate of approximately thirty-two percent on small prey, a figure that places it ahead of every commonly cited mammalian predator save the great white shark and that goes some distance toward explaining the extraordinary impact domestic cats have on songbird populations in regions where they are permitted to hunt outdoors.

---

# Historical Context

The earliest evidence of human-cat cohabitation comes from Cyprus, where archaeologists have recovered a burial dating to approximately ninety-five hundred years before the common era in which a human and a cat were interred together in a manner that strongly suggests a relationship beyond simple coexistence; subsequent millennia saw cats elevated to deity status in Egyptian religious practice, vilified during the European medieval period in association with witchcraft (a development that coincided with significant declines in cat populations and contributed to the rapid spread of bubonic plague via uncontrolled rodent vectors), and rehabilitated during the Victorian era when the first organized cat shows were held in London.

---

# Vocal Communication

A domestic cat possesses a repertoire of approximately twenty-one distinct vocalizations including the meow (which adult cats use almost exclusively in communication with humans rather than other cats), the trill (a friendly greeting employed with both species), the purr (whose function we have addressed previously), the chatter (often emitted in response to observed but inaccessible prey), the hiss (a defensive vocalization indicating discomfort or threat), and the yowl (a multipurpose vocalization used in mating displays, expressions of distress, and the apparently spontaneous nocturnal opinion-sharing for which the species is famous).

---

# Visual Documentation

A representative photographic example would ordinarily be inserted at this point in order to provide the audience with concrete imagery rather than abstraction, but in the present prose-only treatment we will simply note that the typical adult domestic cat measures approximately twenty-five centimeters at the shoulder, weighs between four and five kilograms, possesses a coat in one of several common color and pattern variants (tabby, calico, tortoiseshell, solid, bicolor, or pointed), and conveys an aesthetic impression that the entirety of the present document is implicitly attempting to defend.

---

# A Quantitative Model of Cuteness

If we model cuteness as a function of three variables — eye size (which correlates positively with perceived cuteness on a logarithmic scale), softness or fluffiness (measured here in microfibers per square centimeter though no formal unit exists), and dignity (which correlates negatively with perceived cuteness and which uniquely among the variables tends to increase with age) — then the kittens of the species, possessing oversized eyes and minimal accumulated dignity, represent a local maximum, while older cats compensate for their accumulated dignity through what one might call cumulative charisma.

---

# Conclusion and Recommendations

Having established the awesomeness of cats as a defensible position grounded in their anatomical, behavioral, historical, and aesthetic properties, we conclude with three concrete recommendations for the audience: first, to visit a local animal shelter (whose feline residents benefit from socialization regardless of whether adoption follows from the visit); second, to consider sponsoring an older cat (this demographic being simultaneously the hardest to place in homes and the easiest to live with on a day-to-day basis); and third, to share information about trap-neuter-return programs, which represent the single most effective intervention currently available for the welfare of stray and feral cat populations worldwide.
